================================================================================
1. awesome-open-ended  —  the curated source list
================================================================================
Maintainer: Jenny Zhang (https://github.com/jennyzzt)
Source:     https://github.com/jennyzzt/awesome-open-ended

As of this writing the upstream repository publishes no explicit LICENSE file,
so its content is treated as all-rights-reserved. Accordingly, Exodia:
  - stores only factual bibliographic metadata (titles, authors, venues, years,
    and the curator's outbound links), which it links back to the original
    sources rather than republishing upstream prose;
  - does not copy, mirror, or redistribute the upstream README text;
  - prominently credits Jenny Zhang and links to awesome-open-ended on every
    generated page and in this repository.

If the upstream maintainer requests changes to how this project references their
work, those requests take precedence.

================================================================================
2. AI-Scientist-v2  —  idea generation & summarization
================================================================================
Author:  Sakana AI (https://sakana.ai)
Source:  https://github.com/SakanaAI/AI-Scientist-v2
License: The AI Scientist Source Code License, Version 1.0 (December 2025),
         based on the Responsible AI Source Code License v1.1.

Exodia clones AI-Scientist-v2 at build time and invokes its ideation
script as a subprocess. It does not copy AI-Scientist-v2's source into this
repository, so the license's source-redistribution clause is not triggered.

The license requires prominent disclosure when disseminating machine-generated
research content. Exodia satisfies this by:
  - labeling all AI-generated ideas and LLM-derived summaries on the website
    with a visible "AI-generated content" disclaimer;
  - attributing AI-Scientist-v2 and Sakana AI with links wherever such content
    appears.

Use restrictions in that license (surveillance, deepfakes, healthcare decisions,
criminal prediction, undisclosed machine-generated scholarship) are respected.

================================================================================
3. arXiv  —  paper abstracts
================================================================================
Source: https://arxiv.org  /  API: https://info.arxiv.org/help/api

Paper abstracts are retrieved via the arXiv API and shown with attribution
("Abstract via arXiv") and a link back to the arXiv abstract page. Full-text
PDFs are additionally downloaded from arXiv and cached locally (under
data/pdfs/) for analysis only; they are git-ignored, are not committed to this
repository, and are never re-hosted or redistributed — the site continues to
link back to the arXiv abstract page rather than serving any PDF. The client
respects arXiv's rate guidance (no more than one request every three seconds,
a single connection, and a descriptive User-Agent) for both abstract and PDF
requests. Thank you to arXiv for use of its open API.

================================================================================
4. Semantic Scholar  —  citation counts
================================================================================
Source: https://www.semanticscholar.org  /  API: https://api.semanticscholar.org

Citation counts (and influential-citation counts) are retrieved via the
Semantic Scholar Graph API and stored as factual integers used for the
citation-weighted ("impact") trends. Only these counts are stored; no abstracts
or prose from Semantic Scholar are re-hosted. Requests are batched and
rate-limited; an optional S2_API_KEY raises the rate limit.

================================================================================
5. Video transcripts  —  YouTube captions
================================================================================
For talks/lectures in the curated list that are hosted on YouTube, the caption
track is retrieved and cached locally (under data/transcripts/) for analysis
only. Like the PDFs, transcripts are git-ignored, are not committed to this
repository, and are never re-hosted or redistributed — the site continues to
link back to the original video. Fetching is cache-first and rate-limited.
